Hi Zimin,


It was a pleasure to speak to you and your colleagues at Enron last

Friday.


You asked to see a spread option model generated by SciFinance.  I have

attached a .zip archive that includes a spreadsheet and addin function

for a very simple spread model under Black-Scholes assumptions.  Also

included is the ASPEN specification that produced the code.


Of course, you can generate much more elaborate models by adding

features such as vol surfaces, term structure of correlation, Bermudan

exercise, barriers, cancellable installment premia, etc, to the

specification.


The numerical accuracy is controlled by the parameter 'Accuracy'.  The

code picks nominal values for grid sizes and timesteps, then scales

these nominal values as sqrt(Accuracy).  If the code converges

quadratically in the grid size and timesteps as expected theoretically,

then we expect error ~ Accuracy^(-1).  This is verified by the table

below:


   Accuracy       V      V-V_Inf    CPU sec

    0.2500     9.9618     0.6514     0.5557

    0.5000     9.9295     0.3245     1.4647

    1.0000     9.9136     0.1637     3.9660

    2.0000     9.9055     0.0819    10.9733

    4.0000     9.9013     0.0400    31.5075

       Inf     9.8974          0        Inf


The value for Accuracy=Inf is extrapolated via a linear fit in

Accuracy^(-1).  That the error scales exactly as Accuracy^(-1) is proof

of the theoretically expected convergence.  In fact, because the

convergence is smooth and monotonic, we can extrapolate to the

continuous result using two very cheap calculations.  Using the

Accuracy=0.25 and Accuracy=0.5 results, we can extrapolate:


V_Inf ~ 2*V(Accuracy=0.5) - V(Accuracy=0.25)

      = 2*9.9295 - 9.9618

      = 9.8972


and achieve this result in about 2 sec.  My analytic approximation

yields V_analytic ~ 9.89779.  Thus, we are well under 0.01% error.

While the fd code is a bit slower than the analytic, it can handle all

sorts of additonal features as noted above, with very little increase in

CPU time.


Let me know if you have any questions.


best,

Curt


